-- Vietnam’s Stocks: Binh Duong Mineral, Elcom, Son Ha, Tan Tao
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2012-01-03T05:46:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-03/vietnam-s-stocks-binh-duong-mineral-elcom-son-ha-tan-tao.html
Shares of the following companies had
 unusual (VNINDEX)  moves in  Vietnam trading. (VNINDEX)  Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close in  Ho Chi Minh City .  The VN Index, the benchmark measure of the Ho Chi Minh City
Stock Exchange, fell 0.4 percent to 350.00.  Binh Duong Mineral and Construction Joint-Stock Co. (KSB)  , a mining and building company, slid 4.9 percent to 35,300
dong, the lowest close since Aug. 4.  PXP Vietnam Fund Ltd. (VNF)  will
cut its stake in Binh Duong to 5 percent from 6.6 percent
starting Jan. 5 to March 2, according to a statement on the
exchange’s website.       Elcom Corp. (ELC)  (ELC VN), which offers telecommunications,
 information technology , automation and electronics products and
services, dropped 4.8 percent to 30,000 dong, the most since
Dec. 8. Elcom cut its 2011 after-tax profit target by 43 percent
to 111.3 billion dong ($5.3 million), according to a filing with
the bourse. The company also lowered its 2011 sales target by 46
percent to 506.1 billion dong.       Son Ha International Corp. (SHI)  (SHI VN), which manufactures
stainless-steel plumbing products, gained 4.4 percent to 4,800
dong. The company plans to buy back 500,000 shares from Jan. 9
to March 7, according to an exchange statement.       Tan Tao Investment Industry Corp. (ITA)  (ITA VN), an industrial
zone operator, gained 4.6 percent to 6,800 dong. General
Director Thai Van Men plans to buy 10 million shares from Jan. 6
to March 6, according to an exchange filing.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
